ith physical and emotional trauma.Three interrelated concepts frame the book’s attempt to “stay” in the moment of looking at visual cultures of survival. First, the concept of the war in-between captures those interstitial spaces of war where violence and survival persist side-by-side. Second, this book expands the concept of indexicality to consider how images of the in-between rely on a range of indexical traces to produce alternative visualities about survival and endurance. Third, the book introduces an asymptotic analysis to explore the value in getting close to the diverse experiences that comprise the war in-between, even if the horizon line of experience is always just out of reach.Exploring the capaciousness of survival reveals that there is more to feel and engage in war images than just mangled bodies, collapsing buildings, and industrialized death. The War In-Between, Kozol argues, offers not a better truth about war but an accounting of visualities that arise at the otherwise unthinkable junction of conflict and survival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMilitarism on television. 0aMilitarism. 0aViolence in motion pictures. 0aViolence on television. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aCinema & Media Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAsymptotic Approach.  aCritical Military Studies.  aIn-Betweenness.  aIndexicality.  aVisual Cultures of War.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531507251?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531507251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531507251/original  a978-3-11-075168-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-all